healthAttributeFeedbacks.feedbackTypeTypeName: Feedback that is giving an observation
healthAttributeFeedbacks.whyIsThisImportant:
Your blood glucose level is higher than what it should be, which may lead to numerous medical complications. Make an appointment with your healthcare provider to discuss your results. To improve your HbA1c level, follow a healthy diet, work towards reaching and maintaining your ideal body weight and do at least 150 minutes (5 sessions of 30 minutes) of exercise every week, with your healthcare provider’s permission.
Not controlling diabetes can damage the vessels that supply blood to important organs, like the heart, kidneys, eyes, and nerves. 
Glycosylated (or glycated) haemoglobin, known as HbA1c is a form of haemoglobin used primarily to monitor a persons' glucose control over a period of time. A simple lab test is performed that shows the average amount of glucose in your blood over the last two or three months. It is the most useful measure to assess the success of a diabetics' treatment and level of blood glucose control.

recommendations.friendlyValue: Blood sugar well controlled - HbA1c measurement below 6.5 %

healthAttributeFeedbacks.feedbackTypeTypeName: Feedback that is giving an observation
healthAttributeFeedbacks.whyIsThisImportant:
Too much alcohol can cause accidents, memory loss, tremors and possibly liver disease. It is important to drink only in moderation or to even abstain from drinking alcohol for your overall health.  Maintain your moderate intake of alcohol for a healthy lifestyle.  
Remember that a standard alcoholic drink contains10 grams of alcohol, and this can be estimated to be:
-1 can of beer (340ml)
-1 small glass of red or white wine (120ml)
-1 small glass of sherry (50ml)
-1 metric tot of spirits (25ml)
-1 small glass of liqueur (25ml)

recommendations.friendlyValue: 2 standard drinks a day or less
